    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="408"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d408">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/3047</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BCAdR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Barclay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1387</seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>His Britannic Majesty’s Chargé d’Affaires presents his compliments to the Acting
                    Secretary of State and has the honour to inform him, by direction of His
                    Majesty’s Principal Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs, that His Majesty’s
                    Government have received and considered the Memorandum from the State Department
                    (undated) which was received at this Embassy on the 19th November last, on the
                    subject of Liberia.<note n="2" xml:id="d408fn2">For the substance of this
                        memorandum (sent also to the French Embassy), see <ref
                            target="frus1918#pg_545">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1918, p. 545</ref>.</note> His
                    Majesty’s Government appreciate the force of the United States’ contention and
                    suggest, therefore, that the subject might be considered with other analogous
                    questions at the approaching Peace Conference. The United States Embassy in
                    London, who have enquired the views of His Majesty’s Government on the
                    proposals, have been informed similarly.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-15">December 15,
                            1918</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
